did.abstract: Rudolf Carnap made substantial contributions in the areas of constructional theories, physicalism, the epistemological foundations of physics and mathematics, the syntactical structure of language, semantics, modal logic, and probability theory. Throughout his career he stressed the importance of formal analysis as the key to solving philosophical problems. His papers include extensive correspondence covering his entire life and career, lecture outlines for courses that he taught in Vienna, Prague, and the U.S.; and manuscript drafts and typescripts both for his published works and for many unpublished writings. Digital reproductions of this collection are available online.

bioghist.head: Biography
bioghist.p: Born in 1891 in Ronsdorf, Germany, Rudolf Carnap was educated at the Universities of Freiburg and Jena. He studied mathematics, philosophy, and physics, completing his doctoral thesis, Der Raum, in 1921. Before immigrating to America in 1935, Carnap held positions in Vienna and Prague, where he laid the foundations for his own logical empiricism and participated actively in the discussions of the Vienna Circle. After arriving in the United States, Carnap taught at the University of Chicago until 1952, was a fellow at the Institute for Advanced Study from 1952 to 1954, and held a position at UCLA from 1954 until his death in 1970.

Carnap made substantial contributions in the areas of constructional theories, physicalism, the epistemological foundations of physics and mathematics, the syntactical structure of language, semantics, modal logic, and probability theory. Throughout his career he stressed the importance of formal analysis as the key to solving philosophical problems.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: The Carnap Papers contain some 10,000 pages of letters to and from Carnap, which cover his entire life and career. Since Carnap relied heavily on the mail to discuss important philosophical problems, he corresponded with hundreds of other scholars, among them Herbert Feigl, Carl Gustav Hempel, Felix Kaufmann, Otto Neurath, and Moritz Schlick. A substantial collection of photographs taken throughout Carnap's life depicts him, his relatives, and a number of thinkers with whom he worked closely.

Among Carnap's student notes, perhaps the most interesting come from his seminars with Frege, which were devoted to the Begriffsschrift and the role of logic in mathematics. Also available are Carnap's notes from Russell's seminar at Chicago and notes he took from discussions with Quine, Tarski, GÃ¶del, Hempel, Jeffrey, Heisenberg, and many others.

More than 1,000 pages of lecture outlines for courses that Carnap taught in Vienna, Prague, and the U.S. trace his development as a teacher. Moreover, the collection includes manuscript drafts and typescripts both for his published works and for many unpublished papers and books. In addition, two unpublished papers represent first formulations of Carnap's Aufbau. "Quasizerlegung" ("Quasianalysis," 1932, 21 pp.) outlines the analytical methods for defining quality classes, and "Vom Chaos zur Wirklichkeit" ("From Chaos to Reality," 1922, 14 pp.) represents his first attempt at a construction system using more than six basic relations, instead of one as in the Aufbau. "Topologie der Raum-Zeit-Welt" (Topology of the Space-Time World, 1924) is Carnap's 104-page attempt at a logical reconstruction of the space-time framework of modern physics without using numbers. These are only a few examples of Carnap's many unpublished papers.

The paper's correspondence and manuscripts measure 44.5 linear feet. Much material is written in an outdated German shorthand (the Stolze-Schrey system), which Carnap used extensively since his student days.

acqinfo.head: Acquisition Information
acqinfo.p: The papers were acquired from Carnap's daughter Hanna Carnap-Thost in 1974.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The Rudolf Carnap Papers are arranged into 28 series. Detailed scope and content notes can be found at each series level. When the Carnap Papers were initially processed, the intention was to preserve as much as possible Carnap's original filing system (and occasionally lack thereof) as to the order, content, and titles of the file folders. Therefore, unrelated items may appear in series groupings. In addition, some series may partially repeat in subject matter or format.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series comprises a variety of documents ranging from Carnap's early diaries, recording his experiences as a soldier during World War I, to European travel brochures from the late 1960s, political newspaper clippings, and administrative material concerning Carnap's late years at UCLA.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: The photographs represented in this series span Carnap's whole life, from his early years of his participation in the youth movement "Sera Kreis" to his later years in California. The images cover both personal and professional events, and many document Carnap's and Ina's extensive travels in Europe and the United States. Depicted are also Carnap's family members, friends, and colleagues. The original arrangement and titles of the photographs were preserved. Please note, therefore, that despite the general topical grouping, some unrelated images can be found in each group.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series is divided into 5 subseries. Subseries 1 comprises personal correspondence with Maue Gramm, Elisabeth Carnap-SchÃ¶ndube (a.k.a. Chacha, Carnap's first wife), Carnap's mother Anna Carnap, Carnap's children, family members, and friends, including Carnap's diaries written in the German Stolze-Schrey shorthand system. The diaries are dating from 1911 until his death in 1970. Subseries 2 contains personal and professional correspondence ranging from 1947 to 1970. Subseries 3 holds drafts and correspondence for the International Colloquium on the Philosophy of Science in London in 1965. Correspondence with publishers is featured in subseries 4, while subseries 5 contains early correspondence with individuals and institutions, dating from the years 1908 to 1935.

did.unittitle: Early Manuscripts, Politische Rundbriefe, and Vienna Circle Records

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series centers mostly around Carnap's earlier manuscript drafts, including early outlines of his later published works, as well as minutes of Vienna Circle meetings and the Vienna Circle voting sheets on Wittgenstein's Tractatus. Included are also Carnap's early Politische Rundbriefe from 1918, in which he initiated and promoted political discussions among his friends about the future of Europe and understanding among nations after the end of World War I. Folder headings starting with "Excerpts" followed by an individual's name and title appear to be notes Carnap took on that author's particular work or seminars. The original notes are usually in shorthand but some transcriptions do exist.

scopecontent.p: Featured here is a variety of material reflecting Carnap's research in the area of probability, specifically during his later years. Many of the drafts relate to articles later published in the work Studies in Inductive Logic and Probability, such as the Carnap's manuscript "An Axiom System of Inductive Logic." This piece later evolved into "The Basic System of Inductive Logic, Part I," and "The Basic System of Inductive Logic, Part II," published in Studies in Inductive Logic and Probability, Vol. I and II respectively. Included are also correspondence and manuscript drafts of other contributing authors such as Haim Gaifman, John Kemeny, JÃ¼rgen Humburg, and Richard Jeffrey, and discussion notes with Gordon Matthews and Lary Kuhns.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series covers a range of Carnap's writings and publications projects, including some dissertations written by others in subseries 1. Subseries 2 features probablity papers and notes, authored by Carnap and others. Subseries 3 comprises Schilpp material, notes, and printing-proofs for various works. Finally, subseries 4 contains correspondence with publishers, drafts and page-roofs, lecture notes, Frege seminar notes, and the handwritten letter by Bertrand Russell summarizing his work "Principia Mathematica."

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: The Name Index gives the user a broad picture of the many people Carnap knew or with whom he corresponded from all over the world and throughout his life. The aim of this index is to make the Rudolf Carnap Papers more accessible to scholars. To do this we have compiled this list of names from Carnap's correspondence, notes he made on people or their works, clippings which Carnap saved from magazines and newspapers, and so on. The list is limited to the names of people, i.e., philosophers, publishers, friends, students, and others, showing Carnap's wide-ranging interests and interactions.
The names are arranged alphabeticaly. Beside each name is a number in parantheses which indicates the number of items the name occurs in the specific file.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Carnap organized his collection of offprints of other authors into two alphabetized series which we have arbitrarily designated as "Series A" and "Series B". A third group, made up of offprints found later in archival processing in several locations such as among his books or mixed in with his longer runs of journals, have been artificially collected together as "Series C". Usually, Carnap wrote the name of the author in blue pen in block capital letters on the top left of the offprint and underlined it in red. He also frequently wrote on the top right his signature "Carnap" in script in pencil, with a date, presumably the date he received it. Based on these dates, Series A and Series B seem to have been put together concurrently. See, for example, offprints by Kuroda in Box 74 and 98 which were received on the same date, cover similar topics, and yet are filed into two different series. It is not clear what distinguishes the two series since the dates are largely overlapping, the same authors are represented in both (though not the same publications), and both last over the course of his career both in Chicago and Los Angeles.
Sub-series 4 is a collection of offprints of Carnap's own publications, organized chronologically, with notes regarding if and how much he annotated them.
